{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"6da4ace9-37da-40c5-8878-efb2d6573806","content":"\n\nIn your `App.xaml.cs`, override `CreateWindow` and subscribe to the lifecycle events on the returned `Window`:\n\n```csharp\nprotected override Window CreateWindow(IActivationState? activationState)\n{\n    var window = base.CreateWindow(activationState);\n\n    window.Created       += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(\"Window Created\");\n    window.Activated     += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(\"Window Activated\");\n    window.Deactivated   += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(\"Window Deactivated\");\n    window.Stopped       += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(\"Window Stopped\");\n    window.Resumed       += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(\"Window Resumed\");\n    window.Destroying    += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(\"Window Destroying\");\n    window.Backgrounding += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(\"Window Backgrounding\");\n\n    return window;\n}\n```\n\n**Typical flow:**\n\n| Transition | Events fired |\n|---|---|\n| App launch | `Created` → `Activated` |\n| User switches away | `Deactivated` → `Stopped` |\n| User returns | `Resumed` → `Activated` |\n| App closed | `Deactivated` → `Stopped` → `Destroying` |\n\n> **Note:** `Backgrounding` is iOS/Mac Catalyst only — use it to save state before the OS may terminate the process. On Android/Windows it won't fire.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"b24b1141-c61a-4586-bc5d-233558137883","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about .NET MAUI Window lifecycle events and how to subscribe to them for logging/debugging. This is a general knowledge question — I can answer it directly without needing to explore any codebase.","outputTokens":422},"id":"7a7bb816-e996-4100-ab24-620e323301b1","timestamp":"2026-04-04T00:40:49.864Z","parentId":"66b66967-43a2-4420-9887-d48b56ec86f6"}
